title: For Trade:  Stainless Desert Eagle .357 Magnum
postcontent:
Here's an interesting piece of Magnum Research history. This is a .357 Magnum Mark I pistol from 1985. It has a 6" Magnaported barrel and Millet adjustable sights (white outline rear and bright orange front). It comes with one stainless mag and one blued mag. Comes with the original box, literature, cleaning rod, brush and gas system scraping tool. The gun has a "stainless' appearance and that's where the story gets interesting.

The Desert Eagle serial numbers began at "3000." The suffix "S" was used for "stainless guns." This pistol is serial 309x - S, making it one of the first 100 "stainless" Desert Eagles to ever be imported into this country. According to Magnum Research, these old guns that were catalogued as "stainless" were actually stainless steel cast frames along with Satin Nickel plated barrels and slides (made of chromoly steel). This one has black accents and it looks sharp. It handles screaming full-power .357 loads like a champ and recoils like a 9mm pistol. It's a ton of fun to shoot; nobody has shot it without having a huge smile on their face afterwards. Someone in the past 30 years ground down the sharp edge inside the trigger guard on the right side of the frame. If you're looking for a solid shooter that looks great, this is it!

It isn't very common to come across the "stainless" MKI in .357MAG, let alone one with the Millet sights and Magnaport factory upgrades. In fact, it was several years before I came across this one. I think it's safe to call it "rare" but this one is a shooting piece, not a collector's piece.

I don't want to sell it, but I would consider trades, plus or minus cash for:

postcontent: Rare Hyem over/under combo gun . This is a 7.65 rimmed caliber rifle under a 16ga. standard 2 3/4" chamber shotgun . I believe this to be a model 55 BF . This fine specimen has a beautifully engraved coin finish receiver with a running deer on the left side and two running hares on the right side . It has a matte rib with a folding rear sight on 23 3/4 inch barrels with excellent bores and a set trigger for the rifle barrel.The stock has fine skip line checkering , a horn grip cap , a horn butt plate marked Heym , and a horn trigger guard . There are cocking indicators on both sides of the side plates , a top tang safety , extractors but no ejectors . Length of pull to front trigger is 14 1/4" . Proof marks and stamps include the digits "1167" , month and year of manufacture , 16/70 meaning 16ga/70mm chamber (70mm is 2 3/4"). The place of manufacture is indicated by the words "F.W.Heym-Minnerstadt" engraved on the bottom of the action . This auction includes a finely made Galazan case , snap caps for both rifle and shotgun chambers , RCBS reloading dies , 11 rounds of loaded ammo in RWS cases , 28 pieces once fired RWS cases , and 120 pieces of new RWS brass . I have a lot of pics , so please ask . I have hunted with this combo gun so there are some very minor handling marks . Some of the metal has plum color to it because of age but the bluing is all there . I'd rate the overall condition at 98% . The ammo for the rifle has been loaded to shoot at center point of impact at 100 yards . There has been less than a few rounds shot through this piece . It has been well maintained as well . Please ask questions before you buy . I'm a non ffl holder . Your dealer must accept from a non-licensee and I must have a copy of FFL license for shipping .
